Securing Images with Least Privilege
Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Apply security best practices using the principle of least privilege
Implement image provenance to verify image authenticity
Perform cache cleanup to reduce attack surface
Scan container images for vulnerabilities using Podman
Create and run containers with minimal base images and non-root users
Prerequisites
Linux system with Podman installed (v3.0+)
Basic understanding of container concepts
Internet access to pull container images
sudo privileges for system configuration
Lab Setup
Verify Podman installation:

podman --version
Expected Output: Version number (e.g., 3.4.4)

Create a working directory:

mkdir secure_lab && cd secure_lab
Task 1: Scan Images for Vulnerabilities with Podman
Subtask 1.1: Pull a Sample Image
podman pull docker.io/library/nginx:latest
Subtask 1.2: Scan the Image
podman scan nginx:latest
Expected Output: Vulnerability report showing CVEs and severity levels

Subtask 1.3: Interpret Results
Review the output for:
Critical vulnerabilities (CVSS score ≥ 9.0)
High vulnerabilities (CVSS score 7.0-8.9)
Package names and versions affected
Task 2: Remove Package Caches
Subtask 2.1: Create a Dockerfile with Cache Cleaning
FROM docker.io/library/nginx:latest

# Remove package caches
RUN rm -rf /var/cache/apt/* /var/lib/apt/lists/*
Subtask 2.2: Build the Optimized Image
podman build -t nginx_clean .
Subtask 2.3: Verify Reduced Image Size
podman images
Expected Outcome: The new image should be slightly smaller than the original

Task 3: Use Minimal Base Images
Subtask 3.1: Create Dockerfile with Alpine Base
FROM docker.io/library/alpine:latest

RUN apk add --no-cache nginx && \
    rm -rf /var/cache/apk/*
Subtask 3.2: Build and Compare Sizes
podman build -t nginx_alpine .
podman images | grep nginx
Expected Outcome: Alpine-based image should be significantly smaller than Debian-based

Task 4: Run Container as Non-Root User
Subtask 4.1: Create User in Dockerfile
FROM docker.io/library/alpine:latest

RUN apk add --no-cache nginx && \
    adduser -D nginxuser && \
    chown -R nginxuser:nginxuser /var/lib/nginx

USER nginxuser
Subtask 4.2: Build and Run Securely
podman build -t nginx_nonroot .
podman run -d --name secure_nginx -p 8080:80 nginx_nonroot
Subtask 4.3: Check Running Processes
podman exec secure_nginx ps aux
Expected Outcome: Nginx processes should show running under nginxuser not root

Task 5: Implement Image Provenance
Subtask 5.1: Generate Image Signature
podman image sign --sign-by your@email.com nginx_nonroot
Subtask 5.2: Verify Signature
podman image trust show
Expected Outcome: Should display your signed image in the trust store

Cleanup
podman stop secure_nginx
podman rm secure_nginx
podman rmi nginx nginx_clean nginx_alpine nginx_nonroot
Conclusion
In this lab, you've implemented critical container security practices:

Scanned images for vulnerabilities using Podman's native tools
Reduced attack surface by cleaning package caches
Used minimal base images to decrease potential vulnerabilities
Implemented least privilege by running containers as non-root users
Established image provenance through signing and verification
These techniques help create more secure container deployments while adhering to the principle of least privilege.

Troubleshooting Tips
If scan fails, ensure you have the latest podman version
For permission issues, use --privileged flag during development only
If Alpine packages fail, check for correct package names with apk search
For signing errors, configure GPG first with gpg --gen-key
